title.narrative: CAPACITIES OF KEY CHILD PROTECTION SERVICE PROVIDERS

description.narrative: By 2019, capacities of keychild protection service providers -medical, psychosocial and legal, including CSOs - are strengthened to provide quality and coordinated services to at-risk and child victims, including in emergencysituations., which contributes to Access To Justice, Harmful Practices (Fgm/C And Child Marriage), Prevention And Response Services For Violence Against Children, Prevention Of Harmful Practice, Promotion Of Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being And Justice, Promotion Of Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being And Justice (Covid), Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect, Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Data, Research, Evaluation And Knowledge Management, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2022, 70% of children (girls and boys), the most vulnerable in priority intervention areas, are protected from violence, including in emergency situations, and families adopt protective behaviours.

title.narrative: By 2019, capacities of keychild protection service providers -medical, psychosocial and legal, including CSOs - are strengthened toprovide quality and coordinated services to at-risk and child victims, including in emergencysituations.

description.narrative: 1,830 acteurs-clés de la protection de l’enfant (736 femmes) ont été renforcés en capacités pour délivrer des services de protection de qualité aux enfants victimes de violences, abus et exploitation en Guinée, y compris dans les zones d’urgence (Nzérékoré). Il s’agit de 442 travailleurs sociaux (153 femmes);; 72 parents (43 femmes);; 425 agents communautaires (234 femmes) ; 770 professionnels des agences de l’ONU et des partenaires humanitaires (297 femmes);; 121 professionnels de justice (9 femmes) dont les avocats et les magistrats. Ils ont été formés en compétences diverses pour fournir des services de protection aux enfants. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:02/02/2022
